  "local_port": 58170,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some best resume?",
  "response": "Creating a strong resume involves presenting your skills, experience, and qualifications in a clear, concise, and professional manner. Here are some best practices for crafting an effective resume:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Choose the Right Format**\n- **Chronological Resume**: Focuses on work history, listing jobs in reverse chronological order. Best for candidates with a consistent work history.\n- **Functional Resume**: Emphasizes skills and accomplishments rather than work history. Ideal for career changers or those with employment gaps.\n- **Combination Resume**: Blends chronological and functional formats, highlighting skills and work history. Suitable for experienced professionals.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Start with a Strong Header**\n- Include your name, phone number, email address, and LinkedIn profile or portfolio link (if applicable).\n- Use a professional email address (e.g., firstname.lastname@gmail.com).\n\n---\n\n### **3. Write a Compelling Summary or Objective**\n- **Summary**: A brief 2\u20133 sentence overview of your key skills, experience, and career goals. Tailor it to the job you\u2019re applying for.\n  Example: *\"Results-driven marketing professional with 5+ years of experience in digital advertising, campaign management, and data analysis. Proven track record of increasing ROI by 25% for global brands.\"*\n- **Objective**: Suitable for entry-level candidates or career changers, focusing on your career goals and how they align with the company.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Highlight Your Work Experience**\n- List jobs in reverse chronological order (most recent first).\n- Use **action verbs** (e.g., managed, developed, implemented) and quantify achievements with numbers, percentages, or specific outcomes.\n  Example: *\"Increased sales revenue by 15% through targeted email marketing campaigns.\"*\n- Tailor your experience to the job description by using relevant keywords.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Showcase Your Skills**\n- Include a mix of **hard skills** (e.g., Python, Adobe Photoshop, project management) and **soft skills** (e.g., teamwork, communication, problem-solving).\n- Align skills with the job requirements.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Include Education and Certifications**\n- List degrees, certifications, and relevant coursework.\n- Include the institution name, degree earned, and graduation date (or expected date).\n\n---\n\n### **7. Add Optional Sections (If Relevant)**\n- **Projects**: Highlight relevant projects or freelance work.\n- **Volunteer Work**: Showcase community involvement or leadership roles.\n- **Awards and Honors**: Mention any recognitions.\n- **Languages**: List languages you\u2019re proficient in (if applicable).\n\n---\n\n### **8. Keep It Clean and Professional**\n- Use a simple, easy-to-read font (e.g., Arial, Calibri, or Times New Roman).\n- Stick to a 10\u201312-point font size.\n- Use bullet points for readability.\n- Limit the resume to **1\u20132 pages** (1 page for less experience, 2 pages for extensive experience).\n- Save the file as a PDF to preserve formatting.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Tailor It to the Job**\n- Customize your resume for each job application by emphasizing relevant skills and experience.\n- Use keywords from the job description to pass applicant tracking systems (ATS).\n\n---\n\n### **10. Proofread**\n- Check for spelling, grammar, and formatting errors.\n- Ask a friend, mentor, or professional to review it.\n\n---\n\n### **Sample Resume Structure**\n1. **Header**: Name, Contact Information\n2. **Summary/Objective**: Brief statement\n3. **Work Experience**: Job title, company, dates, and bullet points\n4. **Skills**: Technical and soft skills\n5. **Education**: Degree, institution, graduation date\n6. **Additional Sections**: Certifications, projects, volunteer work (optional)\n\n---\n\nBy following these best practices, you can create a resume that stands out to hiring managers and increases your chances of landing an interview.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
